Introduction:

Cache memory is used in order to reduce the average memory access time by storing the data that are frequently accessed closer to the memory. However, this cache needs to be managed. In order to manage the cache, various cache operations are used like hits, misses and memory access. These operations need a control or management mechanism. 
In the project we developed, we used a FSM (Finite state machine) to implement a simple cache controller. The FSM can control how the cache react to the read or write requests, can handle hits and misses and also manage the communication with the main memory.
The Simulator was implemented in C++ and the simulator works such that the FSM operated cycle by cycle and it can also show how the cache transitions between the states.

System Design:

The system comprises of 3 main elements:
1.	CPU (Request Generator):  The CPU provides the read and write requests. Each request contains the type(read or write), a 32 bit address and for write operations exclusively, write data.
2.	Cache:  It has a direct mapped structure. It consists of 1024 cache lines. Each line contains valid bit, dirty bit, tag and 4 words. Here 4 words is the block size. 
3.	Main Memory: The main memory is simulated using a map. The main memory responds after a certain amount of delay. In my particular project, the memory latency is equal to 4 cycles. The main memory supports both reading a block or writing on a block.

Cache specifications:

In my project, the cache was designed according to the specifications provided in the textbook. That implies:
•	Cache type: Direct-mapped
•	Write policy: Write-back
•	Allocation policy: Write-allocate
•	Block size: 4 words (128 bits)
•	Total lines: 1024

In the request generator we saw that a 32 bits address was passed. The breakdown of that address is as follows:
Field	Bits	Description
Tag	[31–14]	Identifies memory block
Index	[13–4]	Selects cache line
Word Offset	[3–2]	Selects word in block
Byte Offset	[1–0]	Selects byte


Finite state machine design:

The controller is implemented as a moore device.  So, the output depends only on the current state. 
The states are :
•	IDLE STATE: During this state, the cache waits for a cpu request. When the request arrives the state transitions to Compare Tag state.
•	Compare Tag: During this state, the FSM extracts index and tag from the address. The compare tag state also checks the valid and dirty bits. 
If HIT:
Read → return data
Write → update data and set dirty bit
Transition → IDLE
If MISS:
If dirty → Write back state
Else → Allocate state
•	Write back:  Writes the dirty block to memory. After writing a block, it waits for memory latency cycles. After completing write back , the state transitions to Allocate state.
•	Allocate: In this state, the controller fetches block from the memory and updates cache line: 
valid=1;
dirty=0;
tag also updated.
		then the state transitions to the Compare tag state.





