Implementation:

FSM Implementation:
The finite state machine was implemented using an enum State. It was controlled using a switch-case structure and the state transitions occurred on every simulation cycle. 
 


The cache was implemented using structure declaration:
 
The CPU request was also declared as a struct and contained a bool indicating where the request was read or write, an address, a write data and a label.
The address was decoded into index and tag by right shifting it by 4 bits and 14 bits respectively. We had to AND the value of right shift 4 with 0x3FF because the binary of 0x3FF is 00000011 11111111 where 10 bits are set to 1. So I can obtain the 10 bits from the result. 

Memory Simulation:  The memory was simulated using a map. It simulated the block transfers and was controlled using a countdown timer names memTimer. The main memory had 2 functions; one to read the block and the other to write the block. 
The cache controller divides each of the memory address into index and tag using the method mentioned earlier and verifies whether the data requested by the CPU is present or not. In the run loop, the controller stays in IDLE STATE. After fetching a request, it moves to compare tag state where it checks for the cache hit or miss. If it hits, it reads or writes the data based on the request. If the data is written the cache line is marked dirty. If the cache misses, it checks where the line is dirty or not. If the existing cache line is both valid and dirty, then it decides to write back first then allocate. Other wise, It directly allocates. During write back, the dirty data is written on the main memory and during allocate, a new block is fetched to the cache and the meta data like tag, valid bit or dirty bits are updated accordingly. In this way all the requests are handled.  Also memTimer=memory_latency here indicates that this memory operation will take more time. So when memTimer hits 0, it indicates that the memory operation is completed.
Main function: A number of different Test cases were taken and a cache object was created. Then the test cases were run on the cache. we obtain the result in a different txt file. 

Simulation:

Here, 4 test cases were taken.
1.	TC1: Read miss  ---> Cache is empty so block is fetched from the memory. 

FSM sim:
 COMPARE TAG → ALLOCATE → COMPARE TAG → IDLE
2.	TC2: Read hit  ---> Data is found in cache. FSM sim: COMPARE TAG → IDLE
3.	TC3: Write hit  ---> Data updated in the cache so dirty bit set to 1. 
FSM sim: 
COMPARE TAG → IDLE
4.	TC4: Dirty miss  --->Block in cache is dirty, so write back is required before the allocation. 
FSM sim:
COMPARE TAG → WRITE BACK → ALLOCATE → COMPARE TAG → IDLE

Conclusion:

This project successfully demonstrates how a finite state machine controls cache system. The implementation follows the specifications from the textbook and clearly shows how different scenarios like the cache hit or miss or even dirty miss affect the state transitions. It has its fair share of limitations too. Like there is no pipelining or parallel memory operations. Also the memory has a fixed latency. So there are some possible future improvements. They are: 
1.	Since the cache is blocking cache i.e. CPU must wait until one cache operation finishes before starting the next one, we need to implement a non-blocking cache.
2.	A write buffer can be implemented.
3.	The compare and access stages can be separated for the design to be more understandable.
